1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,809
It dawned on me that I was listening to the voice of failure.

2
00:00:02,080 --> 00:00:09,650
It seemed to me W.W. was talking more to convince himself than he was to convert me to his way of thinking.

3
00:00:09,920 --> 00:00:16,929
From then on, I regarded W.W. as an object lesson, a sort of experimental guinea pig.

4
00:00:17,200 --> 00:00:25,890
Rather than buy what he said, I studied him, trying to figure out why he thought the way he did and where such thinking would take him.

5
00:00:26,080 --> 00:00:30,049
I turned my negator friend into a personal experiment.

6
00:00:30,800 --> 00:00:37,329
I haven't seen W.W. in eleven years, but a mutual friend saw him just a few months ago.

7
00:00:37,680 --> 00:00:41,970
W.W. is working as a low-paid draftsman in Washington.

8
00:00:42,240 --> 00:00:45,890
I asked my friend whether W.W. has changed.

9
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:50,530
No, except if anything he's more negative than when we knew him.

10
00:00:50,640 --> 00:00:52,290
He's having a tough go of it.

11
00:00:52,400 --> 00:00:55,809
He has four children, and on his income it's rough.

12
00:00:56,080 --> 00:01:00,370
Old W.W. has the brains to be making five times what he is,

13
00:01:00,560 --> 00:01:03,329
if he just knew how to use those brains.

14
00:01:04,160 --> 00:01:06,049
Negators are everywhere.

15
00:01:06,160 --> 00:01:10,929
Some negators, like the one who almost tripped me, are well-meaning folks.

16
00:01:11,040 --> 00:01:16,610
But others are jealous people, who not moving ahead themselves, want you to stumble too.

17
00:01:16,960 --> 00:01:22,130
They feel inadequate themselves, so they want to make a mediocre person out of you.

18
00:01:22,480 --> 00:01:23,890
Be extra careful.

19
00:01:23,920 --> 00:01:25,410
Study negators.

20
00:01:25,440 --> 00:01:28,610
Don't let them destroy your plans for success.

21
00:01:30,160 --> 00:01:35,329
A young office worker recently explained to me why he had changed carpools.

22
00:01:36,080 --> 00:01:43,329
One fellow, he said, talked about nothing, trip in and trip out, except what an awful company we worked for.

23
00:01:43,520 --> 00:01:46,929
Regardless of what management did, he found fault.

24
00:01:47,120 --> 00:01:50,929
He was negative about everyone from his supervisor on up.

25
00:01:51,120 --> 00:01:53,329
The products we sold were no good.

26
00:01:53,440 --> 00:01:55,809
Every policy had something wrong with it.

27
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,890
As he saw it, absolutely everything had something wrong with it.

28
00:02:00,480 --> 00:02:04,370
Each morning I arrived at work tense and wound up tight.

29
00:02:04,400 --> 00:02:11,569
And each night, after hearing him preach and rant for forty-five minutes about all the things that went wrong that day,

30
00:02:11,680 --> 00:02:14,209
I got home discouraged and depressed.

31
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:18,209
Finally, I got sense enough to get in another carpool.

32
00:02:18,240 --> 00:02:24,530
It's made a world of difference, for now I'm with a group of fellows who can see two sides to a question.

33
00:02:25,440 --> 00:02:28,209
That young fellow changed his environment.

34
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:30,049
Smart, wasn't he?

35
00:02:30,560 --> 00:02:35,329
Make no mistake about it, you are judged by the company you keep.

36
00:02:35,520 --> 00:02:38,049
Birds of a feather do flock together.

37
00:02:38,240 --> 00:02:40,370
Fellow workers are not all alike.

38
00:02:40,480 --> 00:02:42,850
Some are negative, others positive.
